node.text:
Waterfall-NYC (2021) is a new digital waterfall art installation by Samsung in partnership with d’strict in the center of Times Square. Located at One Times Square, the digital art uses four vertical screens for a total of 350 foot (110m)-tall with more than 11,639 square feet (1081 square meters) when combined. Filmed on August 15, 2021 at 7:00 PM. 

📍One Times Square, Midtown Manhattan, New York City

node.text:
Photo meetup on the 26th floor of Olympia, the new condominium residences still under construction in the heart of historic DUMBO, Brooklyn. Olympia offers open and expansive views of the New York Harbor, Lower Manhattan skyline and the iconic Brooklyn Bridge from the highest crest in the neighborhood. 

Full video on my YouTube channel “NYC loves NYC”

@olympia_dumbo @weareoptimist  #olympiadumbo 

📍30 Front Street, DUMBO, Brooklyn, New York City

node.text:
Summer Streets is an annual car-free event held in August. This year,  the event takes place on August 7th and 14th, 7 AM-1 PM in Manhattan between the Brooklyn Bridge and Central Park. Nearly seven miles of NYC’s streets are open for people to play, run, walk, and bike along Park Avenue and its connecting streets. This video was filmed yesterday during my walk on Park Avenue from 34th Street to 47th Street in Midtown Manhattan. @nyc_dot 

Full video in my YouTube channel “NYC loves NYC”

node.text:
These are the the highlights of my walk in The Ramble yesterday.  You can watch the full video in my YouTube channel (NYC loves NYC). 

Tag someone you’d like to explore this Central Park oasis with.

“The Ramble is the most well-known of Central Park’s woodland landscapes, which offer visitors an experience of the woods in the center of New York City. Its 36 acres were designed to look like the forests of upstate New York and include winding paths and trails, rustic bridges, a meandering stream, dramatic rock outcroppings, and dense plantings. The design of the Ramble was intentionally intricate, with twisting paths that encourage wandering and create a sense of mystery and surprise, but also make it challenging to navigate.”
https://www.centralparknyc.org/locations/the-ramble

📍The Ramble, Mid-Park between 73rd and 79th Streets, Central Park, Manhattan, New York City

node.text:
The 30,000 sq. ft. iconic Times Square digital spectacular known as "Big Kahuna" has a new media art execution titled WHALE No. 2 by @dstrictholdings 
Illuminating the pedestrian plaza, the public media art display transforms the huge screen into a hyper-realistic, undulating ocean environment occupied by an enormous blue whale. The whale is made of water and moves freely and harmoniously among the waves.

Now through July 26. One-minute display every half hour starting at 12 p.m. each day and ending at midnight. By Silvercast Media

📍 Broadway from 45th Street to 46th Street, Times Square, New York City

node.text:
Gorilla is out, cows moo-ve in. 

CowParade is a public art exhibit (through September 30) featuring beautifully painted and imaginatively transformed fiberglass cows by extraordinary artists in the Hudson Yards pasture. A wide variety of 70 artists, eclectic designers and celebrity supporters run the gamut and include such iconic names as CRASH, DAZE, Cey Adams, Dapper Dan, Lady Pink, Moulin Rouge! the musical, Logan Hicks, FIT, and Neil Patrick Harris/David Burtka, Zac Posen and Lizzy Tisch naming just a few. Look for these colorful cows popping up at various iconic New York locations. The CowParade culminates in an auction of the cows on September 30, with all proceeds benefiting God's Love We Deliver. God's Love We Deliver cooks and home-delivers nutritious meals for people in NYC. 
@hudsonyards #cowparade #cowparadenyc @topbunartist 

Meanwhile, King Nyani, the giant bronze gorilla was hauled out last Saturday after 9 months of display at the Hudson Yards. 

📍Hudson Yards, West Midtown Manhattan, New York City

node.text:
Mercer Street in SoHo

Double tap if you love SoHo.

Mercer Street runs north to south through the NoHo and SoHo neighborhoods, from East 8th Street past West Houston Street to Canal Street in Manhattan. The street was previously called First Street and Clermont Street, but was renamed in 1799 for Hugh Mercer, a Scottish-American brigadier general who died at the Battle of Princeton, which came about due to his advice to George Washington to march on Princeton.

📍Mercer St, SoHo, Manhattan, New York City
